@raven-sf3diAll stories and art _are_ political, though, because nothing is made in a vacuum by an unthinking robot. Stories are made by people, who constantly experience life, and art is the expression of those experiences. A simple black line on a white canvas can convey an infinite amount of messages. 

Good art goes beyond simple self-expression and tries to make connections through narrative and imagery. In storytelling, these are themes, characterization, setting, and so on. You simply can't separate the politics from the art because it's an integral part of it. It's the expression of the human condition. THAT is politics.

So it's not a matter of no politics in art, but a matter of do _your_ politics align with the art. As I said, if they don't, that's fine. But let's not pretend that separating politics and art is the moral high ground here. I, for one, would never want to live in a world where the art I view has absolutely nothing to say about anything.

@raven-sf3diWorship post-modernism??? Post-modernism isn't a belief. We live in a post-modern society whether you acknowledge it or not.  
Even if you go back to cave paintings, or Renaissance-era portraits, there is still self-expression and politics that go into them (especially cave paint8ngs 😂).Art is always made by someone, somewhere, under some context. Even when an artist isn’t consciously making a political statement, their work still reflects choices shaped by their environment: what they depict, what they omit, what materials they have access to, what cultural symbols they use, and even who gets to see or afford their art. All of that is political in a broad sense.

Also, I think you need to brush up on the definition of politics. In its broadest sense, politics is about how we live together, how we manage differences, define fairness, and shape our shared world. That last part- how we shape our shared world- is the key to understanding how art and politics are inseparable.

@raven-sf3di @eyespy3001 are we talking about political or propaganda here? I've noticed that many people don't distinguish between the two, and that's a mistake.
Basically, propaganda has two key elements:
- imposing a moral judgment on a topic/character from above (for example, he's evil because you're supposed to think so);
- operating on half-true or false perceptions (for example, ignoring context).

